@Mean Old Lady
Back in the day when English was a little more precise than it is today, one would use the possessive "my" before a consonant, and "mine" before a vowel (just like "a" and "an")--thus "Mine Eleanor," "Mine Edward". Later, this would get re-parsed as "My Nell(eanor)," "My Ned(ward)." Hence, Nell and Ned.

In *Game of Thrones,* the Lord of Winterfell is one Eddard Stark, but his wife still calls him "Ned"; that's how Martin works--take a common name or title, twist it just enough to look fantasy-y, but not so far that it wouldn't shorten differently. (Really, Edward (IV) York, Rex Anglorum 1461-1483, should sue for plagiarism.)

